**Abstract:**
Major essay dated November 18, 1998 titled "On Statements and Statements" opening with Gilson quotation on scholastic philosophism. Comprehensive critique of Searle's speech-act theory focusing on the performative character of statements. Uses extended examples ("The hammer is in the next room," "Your mother is on the phone," childhood accident story) to argue statements in context of action are meant to produce conduct-in-response, not mere understanding. Develops distinction between speculative and practical understanding.

**AI Recommendation:** Major book chapter draft on Searle and statements; see 98-dec-1 variant.

